# diagrams / python-diagrams

python-diagrams (mingrammer/diagrams) is a Python "Diagram as Code" library for cloud/system architecture diagrams. You write Python that instantiates provider nodes (AWS/GCP/Azure/K8s/on-prem/SaaS) and connect them with `>>` / `<<` / `-`; Graphviz renders the result to a static image. The primary deliverable is an image file (PNG by default; SVG/JPG/PDF/DOT also available).

controls do
  diagrams.title: { label: "Title", type: "text" }
  diagrams.outformat: { label: "Output format", type: "select", options: "png, svg, jpg, pdf, dot" }
  diagrams.direction: { label: "Flow direction", type: "select", options: "LR, TB, BT, RL" }
  diagrams.source: { label: "Diagram source", type: "textarea", file: "src/arch.py" }
end

## Required reading
- [Diagrams official documentation](https://diagrams.mingrammer.com/) — official, MIT, by mingrammer (Min-gyu Kim).
- [mingrammer/diagrams source + examples + node catalog](https://github.com/mingrammer/diagrams) — official, MIT, by mingrammer. Use the node catalog to find provider import paths (e.g. `diagrams.aws.compute.EC2`).
- No dedicated Claude SKILL.md exists for python-diagrams; Mermaid/Excalidraw skills target different tools.

## Render
```bash
# Graphviz system binary is required (pip does NOT bundle it)
brew install graphviz
python3 -m pip install diagrams

# render the diagram (writes <filename>.<outformat> in the output dir)
python3 src/arch.py
```

## Failure modes
- `failed to execute "dot"` / `PosixPath('dot')` — Graphviz binary not installed or not on PATH. Run `brew install graphviz` and ensure `dot -V` works.
- Auto-opening an image viewer on render — always pass `show=False` to `Diagram(...)` for headless runs.
- `ModuleNotFoundError` on a provider import — wrong node path; check the node catalog in the repo for the exact module (e.g. `diagrams.aws.database.RDS`).
- Empty or overlapping layout — adjust `direction` (LR/TB) or use `Cluster()` to group related nodes.
- Wrong file extension — the extension is derived from `outformat`, not from `filename`; set `outformat` to control the type.
